FROGS 5 SESSION SHEET FORMAT + TEMPLATE  (WordPad / RTF edition)
How to build a GM session file you can run an entire night from, in WordPad.

This governs STRUCTURE and LOOK. The WRITING GUIDE governs the prose inside the
READ-ALOUD and HANDOUT blocks. Use both.

The job of a session sheet: ONE file, opened in WordPad, that runs the whole night
with nothing else open -- and that reads cleanly AT THE TABLE, out loud, while four
players look at you. Everything inlined. No "see the other doc."

WHY THIS REPLACED THE OLD NOTEPAD FORMAT:
  The old format was pure ASCII, hard-wrapped to 80 columns, tag-greppable. That was
  built for machine inference, not for a human reading live -- at the table it became
  a wall of grey text with no place for the eye to land, and read-aloud hid inside GM
  prose. WordPad gives us size, bold, italic, colour, indent, and spacing, so we build
  the sheet entirely for the GM. (The model reads rich text fine; nothing was lost.)


====================================================================
0  THE WORKFLOW  (how a sheet is made and maintained)
====================================================================

- The deliverable is an .rtf file the GM opens and HAND-EDITS in WordPad. The .rtf is
  the canonical, living doc -- the GM writes notes into it during play.
- First drafts are produced by the generator script `_build_session_rtf.py` (repo
  root): content is written as helper calls (scene/readaloud/handout/gm/bullet/
  statcard/exit), and the script emits clean RTF. This avoids hand-writing fragile
  RTF control words.
- After generation, the .rtf is canonical. Regenerate ONLY before the GM has started
  editing/playing a sheet (a rerun overwrites hand-edits). Once they're in it, edit
  the .rtf directly.
- Visual reference: `Toryggs legacy/SESSION FORMAT SAMPLE.rtf` (one scene, fully
  styled). Open it to see the target.
- Validate every generated .rtf for balanced braces before handing it over (a throwaway
  brace-counter; the build is invalid if final balance != 0).


====================================================================
1  THE VISUAL VOCABULARY  (the element types and what each is FOR)
====================================================================

The whole point is that the GM never HUNTS. Each element looks distinct so the eye
finds it instantly.

SCENE HEADER
  Big (18pt), bold, MAROON, generous space above. Numbered. You navigate the doc by
  these. e.g.  "1   THE LAB, MID-FIGHT -- ROLL INITIATIVE"

"WHAT THIS IS" SUBTITLE
  One italic GREY line directly under the header. Orients the GM in one second: the
  scene's purpose and goal. Not flavour -- function.

>> READ ALOUD  (the single most important element)
  A labelled, indented, ITALIC, BLUE block. Its own label line ">> READ ALOUD" in
  bold. Blank space around it. Long narration is broken into paragraphs INSIDE the
  block so it is never a wall. At the table you should never search for the next thing
  to say -- the blue finds your eye.

>> HANDOUT -- <title>
  Same blue italic block, labelled as a handout. The full in-world text of a journal,
  letter, or note, inlined so you read or paste it without leaving the file.

GM NOTES
  Normal weight, prefixed with a bold maroon "GM:". Kept SHORT -- a beat per note, not
  a paragraph brick. This is your-eyes-only truth and adjudication.

NPC REACTION  ("HOW THEY TAKE IT")
  For any NPC the party brings something to, or negotiates with: the NPC's RESPONSE to
  the likely player moves -- accept / refuse / the big reveal -- written as behaviour +
  an actual line, not just the offer. A social scene is branches, not a monologue. The
  absence of this element is what makes an NPC read as a vending machine (the Maven
  failure: we wrote what she offered, never how she TOOK the news).

BULLETED BEATS
  One idea per bullet, brown bullet glyph, whitespace between. Discoveries, options,
  consequences -- anything scannable becomes bullets, never prose.

ROLLS / MECHANICS -- BOLD INLINE
  Bold the roll so it jumps: **Hard Guile (-4)**, **Standard Magic**, **Very Hard
  Agility (-6)**. Never a fixed target number (see section 3).

STAT / MECHANIC CARDS
  A bordered, monospace block set apart from the prose, so a fight or a sub-system
  reads like a card you glance at, not a sentence you parse. Used for stat blocks AND
  for any tight rules widget (an alert ladder, a release combination, etc.).

LABELS (sub-headers within a scene)
  Bold BROWN (or RED for danger/combat), ~13pt. INVESTIGATE / LOOT / THE FIRST KILL /
  COMBAT. They break a long scene into glanceable sections.

EXIT ->
  A bold maroon "EXIT ->" line closing the scene and pointing at the next, e.g.
  "EXIT -> 2  THE OSSUARY". The reader always knows where the scene leads.


====================================================================
2  THE COLOUR PALETTE  (keep it small -- colour is navigation, not decoration)
====================================================================

  MAROON  -- scene headers, EXIT lines, the "GM:" tag. The skeleton you navigate by.
  BLUE    -- READ-ALOUD and HANDOUT blocks. "This is the thing you say/show."
  BROWN   -- labels and bullets. The body structure.
  RED     -- danger labels only (combat, catastrophic stakes). Use sparingly.
  GREY    -- the italic "what this is" subtitle.

If in doubt, fewer colours. Bold carries most of the emphasis; colour marks KIND.


====================================================================
3  STRUCTURAL RULES  (carry over from the old format; still law)
====================================================================

- SELF-CONTAINED. Inline every stat block, NPC line, clue, handout, rule, and
  consequence the night needs. A cross-reference to another file is a failure.
- RUNNABLE MEANS RUNNABLE -- INLINE THE MECHANIC AT EVERY POINT OF USE. If a scene invokes a
  clock, table, or rule that was defined earlier in the document, restate what running it
  actually looks like IN THIS SCENE -- never "see the rules block above" or a bare pointer. A
  GM running this cold, live, will not flip back. (The Fire B failure: the Notice Clock was the
  entire mechanic Scene 5 exists to run, and the scene body never restated it -- only a single
  downstream beat survived. This is the same failure as the load-bearing-scene rule below, in
  mechanical form, and it is especially unacceptable because a complete, self-running module is
  the actual target -- it's what the eventual module-creation tool in the app depends on.)
- NO HARD-WRAP. Let WordPad word-wrap. Hard-wrapping is what made the old bricks.
  Keep paragraphs SHORT and lean on bullets + blank space instead.
- NUMBER EVERY SCENE. Scenes run in order; the reader counts down them.
- NEVER A FIXED TARGET NUMBER. The GM sets DIFFICULTY, never a TN. Always
  "Hard Guile (-4)" / "Standard Magic", never "Guile TN 14". This is the single most
  important mechanical rule of the campaign; it applies in every stat block, puzzle,
  and mechanic on the sheet.
  Difficulty ladder (unified, July 2026): Very Easy +4 / Easy +2 / Standard 0 /
  Hard -4 / Very Hard -6 / Nearly Impossible -8 / Impossible -14 / Mythic -20.
- PROSE OBEYS THE WRITING GUIDE. Inside READ-ALOUD and HANDOUT: present what IS there;
  no "cold" filler; no describing by absence; no omniscience; never narrate a player's
  actions, choices, or conclusions. The sheet hands the table the moment; it never
  spends it for them.


====================================================================
4  THE SCENE TEMPLATE  (TWO archetypes -- pick by what the scene IS)
====================================================================

Every scene is one of two kinds. They share the skeleton (numbered maroon header +
grey "what this is" line) but REQUIRE different bodies. Build to the archetype; never
let a character scene collapse into a list of GM notes.

A. SET-PIECE / LOCATION SCENE  (a room, a fight, a puzzle, a dungeon beat)
  SCENE HEADER (maroon, numbered)
  "what this is" subtitle (grey italic)
  >> READ ALOUD          the place, the moment (blue), broken into paragraphs
  GM: ...                truth + adjudication (short)
  LABEL                  e.g. INVESTIGATE / COMBAT / LOOT
    bullet beats         one idea each
    >> HANDOUT -- title  full in-world text, inlined, opt-in depth
    STAT / MECHANIC CARD  bordered monospace block
  EXIT -> next scene

B. CHARACTER / SOCIAL SCENE  (a camp, an NPC meeting, a farewell, a negotiation)
  SCENE HEADER (maroon, numbered)
  "what this is" subtitle (grey italic)
  >> READ ALOUD          the MOMENT they walk into -- the place, the mood, who is here,
                         and what just changed (blue). A character scene gets a read-
                         aloud too; "no room to describe" is NOT licence to skip it.
  then, PER NPC, a PLAYABLE BEAT -- never a bio:
    LABEL (the NPC)      e.g. MILA / BJORN / MAVEN
    GM:                  one line of "what it is / what it offers"
    a SPOKEN LINE        at least one -- a >> READ ALOUD snippet or  NPC: "dialogue"
    NPC REACTION         for anyone the party engages: how they take the likely moves
  EXIT -> next scene

  THE TEST: could the GM run B cold, off the page, WITHOUT inventing dialogue? If the
  beat is who-they-are and what-mood with nothing to SAY, it is prep, not a scene.

  HARD CONSTRAINT -- EVERY VIGNETTE ROUTES THROUGH A PC, NEVER NPC-TO-NPC. If two NPCs have
  something to develop between them, stage it INSIDE a player's vignette -- never as a
  standalone scene where both participants are GM-controlled. An NPC-NPC scene is not a
  vignette, it's a cutscene: the table spectates instead of playing. (The Fire B failure:
  Ismara+Ylva and Nora+GEAR both collapsed into the GM narrating two NPCs at each other. If an
  NPC thread needs to move, find the PC whose scene it moves inside of -- it always exists;
  Nora's whole vignette sequence should have carried her consultations with Ylva and Ismara
  as color inside HER scene, not as separate NPC-only beats.)

  THE DISTRIBUTION TECHNIQUE -- an NPC arc doesn't have to fit inside ONE PC's vignette. Spread
  it as short appearances across SEVERAL PC vignettes in the same scene block: a beat in one
  PC's scene, a beat in another's, a payoff in a third. This gives the NPC a real throughline
  without ever needing a standalone NPC-to-NPC scene, and it plays more alive at the table than
  one consult delivered in a single sitting. (Origin: Nora's "seeking advice about Orion" arc --
  rather than one separate consult scene, she surfaces briefly in Ismara's vignette, then
  Saijah's, then pays off in her own scene with Orion. Any NPC subplot that would otherwise
  need its own scene is a candidate for this same treatment.)


====================================================================
5  THE LORE-DELIVERY MODEL  (unchanged -- keep the three jobs separate)
====================================================================

A lore drop does up to three jobs. Keep them apart:

  THE CLUE  -- load-bearing; the party needs it to move. Give it its OWN short beat,
    at its point of use, deliverable in ten seconds. NEVER bury a clue inside a long
    READ-ALOUD or HANDOUT. Two short clues at two spots beat one wall in one room.
  THE GIST  -- the one line you say when a FIND is picked up; keeps pace and tells the
    table whether to read further.
  THE HANDOUT -- the full in-world text. Opt-in depth; players read on their own time;
    it never gates the night.

Standing fix for the one failure mode: the clue is never in the dump.


====================================================================
5B  THE CHARACTER-SCENE MODEL  (the second standing failure mode)
====================================================================

Section 5 fixes the lore failure. This fixes the SCENE failure:

  A BEAT IS NEVER A CHARACTER SHEET.

A scene written as character-state -- who the NPC is, what mood they're in, their
psychology -- is PREP, not a runnable scene. At the table it leaves the GM holding a
bio and improvising the whole moment (this is exactly what happened to the camp scene;
the GM had to build it live). Psychology is the skeleton; the scene is the flesh: a
thing to SAY (a read-aloud or a line) and a thing to DO/OFFER, per NPC.

  - WRONG (prep):  "Mila misses her mother; it leaks sideways; she's Warrens-hard."
  - RIGHT (scene): the read-aloud of her on the tailgate + MILA: "Is Windhelm far?
                   ...Hypothetical." + GM: what it tests, who she'll let close.

And an NPC the players bring news to or bargain with needs REACTION beats (how they
take it) or they read as a vending machine. The offer is half a scene; the response
is the other half.


====================================================================
5C  THE LOAD-BEARING RULE  (the third standing failure mode)
====================================================================

If a scene is PLANNED -- if it exists because other scenes were built to lead into it -- it
gets the SAME full treatment as any other numbered scene: real dialogue, real read-aloud, both
branches actually written. It never gets a synopsis with bullet-point outcomes standing in for
the scene itself.

Improv at the table is fine and expected -- that is what live play is for. But a scene that was
BOTHERED TO BE PLANNED and then gets shortchanged in prep isn't improv, it's unfinished work
wearing a scene's shape. Mark these explicitly while drafting (LOAD-BEARING) so effort doesn't
quietly ration itself near the end of a long build, which is exactly when it tends to happen.

  THE FIRE B FAILURE: three prior vignettes (Saijah, Ylva, Ismara) were built specifically to
  walk Nora toward her scene with Orion -- the actual payoff every other beat was pointing at --
  and that scene got two sentences of synopsis instead of a written scene. The setup got full
  treatment; the payoff didn't. That is backwards, and it is the single worst thing this
  document has done to the GM's trust in a draft.


====================================================================
6  STAT / MECHANIC CARDS  (how the bordered blocks read)
====================================================================

Rendered as a bordered, monospace card. One line per attack or ability; numbers
grouped with " | "; long abilities wrap indented. Example content:

  FALSE DRAUGR  x4-6   (TL1-2 Expert) -- Antoine's make, NOT true undead
  HP 35  |  DR 5  |  Immune poison/disease/cold/fear/Alfonso's communion
  Weak FIRE (x2)  |  Sonic-Thunder (staggered 1 rd)
  Might 15   Agility 10   Magic 6   Guile 2 (no mind in here)
  Atk Alchemical Blade -- melee 8; Standard Might or Numbness (-1 Agi, 2 rds)
  Atk Restraining Grapple -- contested Might (Hard -4) -> Restrained; they pile on

Cards also hold non-combat widgets -- an exposure ladder, a release combination -- any
time a tight rules object should be glanced at rather than read.


====================================================================
7  BUILD CHECKLIST  (run before a sheet is "ready")
====================================================================

1. Could you run the whole night without opening another file? If not, inline it.
2. Does every scene have a maroon header + a grey "what this is" line?
3. Is every READ-ALOUD / HANDOUT a distinct blue block, broken into paragraphs, with
   air around it -- never hiding inside GM prose?
4. Are GM notes short bullets/lines, not paragraph bricks?
5. Is every roll a bolded DIFFICULTY, with NO fixed target numbers anywhere?
6. Is every load-bearing fact its own short clue at its point of use -- not buried in
   a read or a handout?
7. Are stat blocks and rules widgets bordered monospace cards, not prose?
8. Does the .rtf validate (balanced braces) and open cleanly in WordPad?
9. Does every READ-ALOUD pass the WRITING GUIDE self-check (no cold, no negation, no
   omniscience, no writing the players' actions, NO NARRATED SUBTEXT -- a character's
   private motive/want/feeling stated in words instead of shown through the bare action;
   full statement: WRITING GUIDE Section IX Rule 0, also in CLAUDE.md Rule 7, AI_README
   Rule 5, AI_REASONING_PATTERNS #16)?
10. Is every scene built to its ARCHETYPE (set-piece vs character/social), and does
    EVERY scene -- camp and social included -- open with a read-aloud moment?
11. Does every NPC beat carry at least one thing to SAY (a line), not just who they
    are? (No beat is a character sheet.)
12. Does every NPC the party engages have REACTION guidance -- how they take the
    accept / refuse / reveal?
13. Does every read-aloud pass the SPOKEN TEST, BREATH TEST, and PUNCHLINE TEST (WRITING
    GUIDE section VII)?
14. Is every vignette driven by or aimed at a PC -- zero standalone NPC-to-NPC scenes?
15. Is every LOAD-BEARING scene (one other scenes were built to lead into) written in full --
    dialogue and read-aloud, not synopsis with bullet outcomes?
16. Is every mechanic a scene invokes restated at ITS point of use, not just pointed at from
    an earlier rules block?
